post_text:
Elgin Mayor David Kaptain live with a few words on the importance of being counted in the Census 2020.
#U46Counts
shared_text:
City of Elgin-Government, City Services and Community News was live.
September 9 at 9:32 AM ·

Please take the time to tune into this live talk from Mayor David Kaptain about the importance of getting everyone in Elgin counted before the counting period ends on September 30 at 9:30 am. Elgin is currently around only 72.1% counted. Laura Bedolla, Census Partnership Specialist, will also be there to answer any questions that will help us maximize our efforts during this last month.
To fill out your Census, visit www.my2020census.gov.
For more information about the Census, visit www.gailborden.info/census.

post_text: Wayne Township offers a wide variety of financial assistance programs, food pantry and community resources to individuals and families living in the Wayne Township service boundaries of Bartlett, Carol Stream, Hanover Park, St. Charles, Wayne and West Chicago. Families in need of food visit the weekly drive-thru food distributions every Wednesday between 10 a.m. and noon. Limited school supplies and backpacks are still available for elementary students. Please call 630-231-7173 for assistance. #WeAreU46

post_text: We understand that (in addition to the Zoom outage) there is a power outage on the north side of Elgin, impacting Coleman Elementary. Our resilient team and families at Coleman are working through this issue as best they can and hope to be back online soon.
text: We understand that (in addition to the Zoom outage) there is a power outage on the north side of Elgin, impacting Coleman Elementary. Our resilient team and families at Coleman are working through this issue as best they can and hope to be back online soon.

post_text: Families: Just FYI, here is the update from Zoom.
shared_text:
STATUS.ZOOM.US
Zoom Status

Zoom
August 24 at 9:27 AM ·

[UPDATE 9:45AM PST]
Everything should be working properly now! We are continuing to monitor the situation. Thank you all for your patience and our sincere apologies for disrupting your day.

[UPDATE 9:15 AM PST]
Thanks for your patience! Meeting and webinar service has been restored for the majority of users.

Some of you may still be unable to sign up for paid accounts, upgrade, or manage your service on our website.
http://status.zoom.us

[UPDATE 8:06 AM PST]
Thanks for hanging in there! We are deploying a fix now. Service should be restored for some users and we’re continuing to complete the fix for any users still impacted. We're sorry about the disruption.

Follow http://status.zoom.us for updates.

[7:32AM PST]
If you're having trouble connecting to Zoom, we have identified the issue and are working on a fix. Please follow status.zoom.us for updates. We're so sorry about the inconvenience.

post_text: U-46 Students: If you and your teacher can not connect to Zoom today due to the widespread Zoom outage, not related to U-46, then please be on the lookout for an email with a link to Google Meet which is another platform for live interactive instruction. We know that many students and teachers have made a connection via Zoom today but for those who are having issues, teachers will be sending students a Google Meet link. Thank you for your patience and understanding. We have also send this message as an email and text to all families.

post_text: School District U-46 will be administering the SAT with Essay to all seniors on Wednesday, Sept. 23 at their home high school. The SAT with Essay is a state of Illinois graduation requirement for all students in the Class of 2021 and their attendance on testing day is expected. By providing the exam on Sept. 23, 2020, students will receive their scores with ample time to apply for early college admittance and scholarships. We will also give seniors the opportunity to take the SAT in April in order to meet graduation requirements. More details are posted on the homepage of high school websites and on the District website at u-46.org/covid.

post_text: Juneteenth became an official state holiday in Texas on January 1, 1980. This was made possible through the efforts of Al Edwards, who was an African American state legislator. Juneteenth then became the first emancipation celebration that was granted an official state recognition. Now, most states and the District of Columbia recognize June 19 as state holiday or observance.
text: Juneteenth became an official state holiday in Texas on January 1, 1980. This was made possible through the efforts of Al Edwards, who was an African American state legislator. Juneteenth then became the first emancipation celebration that was granted an official state recognition. Now, most states and the District of Columbia recognize June 19 as state holiday or observance.

post_text: On this day in 1865, more than two and a half years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed and three months after Confederate General Robert E. Lee surrendered, Union Soldiers in Galveston Texas announced that all enslaved people were free. We remember this day as Juneteenth. Learn more by visiting https://www.juneteenth.com/history.htm.

U-46 High School Families,

The Illinois State Board of Education and the Illinois High School Association have released guidance on the types of in-person activities schools are allowed to host during Phase 3 reopening Illinois. The State guidance allows us to host in-person summer conditioning camps for students with specific conditions. These camps are focused on overall physical activity for students, they are not sport specific. We have decided to host free conditioning camps that will be offered twice a week between Monday and Thursday in two-hour sessions. This will begin Monday, June 22. Schools will be following up with more details later this week.

For more information, please visit bit.ly/U46ConditioningCamps.

Dear South Elgin Families,

We want to share with you the below apology from StageClip, the company that handled our virtual graduation ceremonies. The vice president sent the following email at 4:30 p.m. today to Lela Majstorovic, the Assistant Superintendent for Secondary Schools Instruction and Equity for School District U-46.

Dear Lela,

As discussed on the phone this is our fault and for which the district and the school are in no way responsible. This was caused by a human error. We would like to apologise to the school and the graduating students.

Kind regards and apologies once again.

StageClip

post_text: Mr. and Mrs. Atienza were surprised and touched when Mr. Jim Berger, a teacher at Liberty Elementary School in Bartlett, stopped by to personally congratulate their son Aaron on finishing his 6th grade year. Aaron had Mr. Berger as his 5th grade teacher. So they made this video for him. “Our sons and all U- 46 students are lucky to have such dedicated teachers like them who definitely have a positive impact in their education and future,” said Mr. and Mrs. Atienza, who also thanked Kenyon Woods Middle School history teacher Albert Navarro for his support and recognition of their son Joshua. “During this challenging time we’re facing, we're so grateful for these simple but touching gestures.” #WeAreU46

post_text:
Betty Martiznes, teacher for 29 years currently instructing at Lowrie and Timber Trails Elementary School, has led her distance learning classes from her dining room. She was inspired to use everyday items for educational purposes. The table became a desk, the chairs stored material, and the napkin holder held books. “The home classroom gave me max efficiency,” said Martiznes. “Giving up one space to create another made more sense in today’s uncertain time.”
#WeAreU46

I am so proud of my students for pulling of a virtual choir!! “The Storm Is Passing Over” is usually performed at the end of each spring concert and is so appropriate now. Seniors usually line the front of the stage and alumni join all of the choirs to sing in this tradition. Since that couldn’t happen tonight, one of my amazing senior Beacon Academy students was able to edit this together! I am so grateful for him and his many hours of work on this project!! Enjoy!!

The Educational Programming docents from the Elgin History Museum were nominated for the Volunteer of the Year category for their exceptional service to students from 15 different U-46 schools. Without these docents, the students’ visit to the museum would be a visit to a building full of old stuff! They help the students make connections between themselves and the artifacts they see in the display cases.
#U46Volunteers

Mañana (5/20) a las 7 p.m. el Dr. Ferney Ramírez estará presente en una sesión virtual por parte de District U-46 BPAC para dejarnos saber cómo establecer rutinas positivas en casa y cómo hacer del hogar la mejor escuela. Información muy importante durante el aprendizaje a distancia que presentemente estamos enfrentando y posiblemente en alguna parte del próximo año escolar.

La sesión será en línea por medio de:
-- Zoom - https://bit.ly/BPACWed
-- Facebook Live en el grupo de District U-46 BPAC

No se pierda esta sesión en español. Habrá otra el viernes con diferente tema.
